Deltari Reed Law assessment of the Verdant Depths centers on the deep aquifer connection: the ancient root network taps the same deep aquifer system that feeds the Great Northern Forest's surface springs, creating a biological water-draw that has been operating continuously for thousands of years. The well in the Zone 2 ruins confirms that the aquifer connection was known to pre-civilizational peoples: the well's construction deliberately targets the same aquifer layer the root network uses, without disrupting the root network's access to it. Deltari hydrological assessment: the root network's water consumption is stable because it is a closed-cycle system — water drawn from the aquifer is returned to the surface through transpiration, precipitation capture, and runoff filtration rather than extracted for external use. The Withered Depths blight has disrupted this closed cycle in the contaminated zone: the Conclave's crystal matrices alter root system water transport pathways, causing localized aquifer draw without comparable return cycle, contributing to the blight's expansion as the contaminated zone gradually dries out. The forest's survival matters for the regional water cycle in ways that extend beyond the forest's own territory.
